-- 1. [Problem Restatement] An arithmetic sequence has S₅ = 70 and S₁₀ = 210; determine its first term a. 2. [Key Idea] Write the two given partial sums with the formula Sₙ = n/2·[2a + (n − 1)d] and solve the resulting linear system for a. 3. [Proof] Using Sₙ = n/2·[2a + (n − 1)d]: • For n = 5 S₅ = 5/2·[2a + 4d] = 70 ⇒ 5(2a + 4d) = 140 ⇒ 2a + 4d = 28 … (1) • For n = 10 S₁₀ = 10/2·[2a + 9d] = 210 ⇒ 5(2a + 9d) = 210 ⇒ 2a + 9d = 42 … (2) Subtract (1) from (2): (2a + 9d) − (2a + 4d) = 42 − 28 5d = 14 ⇒ d = 14/5 Insert d into (1): 2a + 4(14/5) = 28 2a + 56/5 = 140/5 2a = 84/5 ⇒ a = 42/5. 4. [Conclusion] The first term of the arithmetic series is a = 42/5.
